paragraphs.text:
%md
### Prepare Dataset

1. Load data
2. View data
3. Clean data 
4. Apply PCA
5. Interpret results
6. Evaluate validity of results

%r

# 1. Load dataset
data(mtcars)

# 2. View dataset

head(mtcars) # print out a few rows
str(mtcars) # look at structure of data
# vs and am are factors rather than numeric

%r
# 3. Clean dataset
# remove non-numeric data i.e factors vs (transmission v vs straight) and am (carberator auto vs man)
library(dplyr)
data <- mtcars %>% select(-c(vs,am))

# 4. Apply PCA
pca <- prcomp(mtcars, center = TRUE, scale.= TRUE) 
# scaling is used to standardize the variance across variables to avoide over-representing high variance variables

# 5. Interpret results
summary(pca)
# Inspect Proportion of Variance
# 60% of variance accounted for by PC1, 24% of variance accounted for by PC2, etc.

# How much variance do you need explained by the least number of components?
## first 1: 60%,  first 2: 84%,  first 3: 89%

paragraphs.text:
%r
# use a screeplot to help decide
screeplot(pca, type="lines")

%r
# Evaluate Kaiser-Guttman Criterion
## Only keep the components for which the Eigenvalue is greater than 1
## EV needs var or sd squared of each component from pca obj
# str(pca) # pca$sdev stores std dev and colnames(pca$rotation) stores PCA name list 

# Which components have eigenvalues greater than 1?
colnames(pca$rotation)[pca$sdev^2>1] # component 1 and 2

# Which variables contribute to a given component?
pca$rotation # for comp1 cyl, disp, hp, wt contribute most

%r
# Visualize variable contributions to component with a biplot
pca %>% biplot(cex=.8) 
# Note hp, cyl, disp, and wt are grouped together

%r
# 6. Evaluate validity
# Compare components to original variables using linear regression
# we will predict mpg using other variables in mtcars dataset
# 1. Create linear model predicting with all variables
fit_1 <- lm(mpg ~ ., data=mtcars)
# 2. Create another linear model comparing only 1st 2 components
components <- cbind(mpg = mtcars[,"mpg"], pca$x[,1:2]) %>% as.data.frame() # create data frame with mpg and component 1 and 2
fit_2 <- lm(mpg ~., data=components)
# 3. Compare models using 4-square value
summary(fit_1)$adj.r.squared
summary(fit_2)$adj.r.squared # pca 1+2 has a better r-squared value when just using the 2 components
